What about the creation of a shiny-like library, but that is fundamentally different supporting hot-reloading and any other modern utilities, while preserving backwards compatibility to shiny?

This is a serious, interesting systems question, and the short answer is:

Yes, this is possible in principle — but only if “backwards compatibility” is interpreted very carefully.

You cannot preserve semantic compatibility with Shiny and get true hot-reloading.
You can preserve API-level compatibility while changing the execution model underneath.

Below is a concrete, realistic design space — not hand-waving.

First: what “backwards compatible” can mean

There are three levels of compatibility:

Level	Possible?	Notes
Syntax compatibility	✅	reactive(), observe(), render*()
Behavioral equivalence	⚠️	Mostly, but edge cases differ
Execution semantics	❌	Must change

A new system cannot preserve Shiny’s execution semantics and still support hot reload.

So the viable goal is:

Same API surface, different runtime

Think: React → Preact, Vue → Solid, Angular → Signals.

The core idea: Shiny as a DSL, not a runtime

Instead of executing Shiny code immediately, you:

Parse + register intent

Build a declarative graph

Compile to a reactive runtime

Version + diff the graph on reload

Shiny today does step 4 → never.

Proposed architecture (high level)
┌───────────────┐
│ User Code     │  shiny-like DSL
└──────┬────────┘
       ↓
┌───────────────┐
│ Graph Builder │  (NOT execution)
└──────┬────────┘
       ↓
┌───────────────┐
│ Reactive IR   │  versioned, diffable
└──────┬────────┘
       ↓
┌───────────────┐
│ Runtime       │  hot-swappable
└──────┬────────┘
       ↓
┌───────────────┐
│ Client        │  DOM diffing
└───────────────┘

Key enabling difference: reactive nodes are data, not closures
Shiny today
observe({
  x <- input$a
  y <- f(x)
})


Closure captures f

Observer is opaque

Cannot be replaced

New system
observe({
  y <- call("f", input("a"))
})


Internally stored as:

{
  "type": "observe",
  "deps": ["input.a"],
  "expr": {
    "call": "f",
    "args": ["input.a"]
  }
}


Now:

Code is data

Can diff

Can replace

Can version

This is the single most important shift.

Hot reload becomes possible

On file change:

Re-parse code

Rebuild IR

Diff old vs new graph

For unchanged nodes:

Preserve state

For changed nodes:

Tear down

Recreate

UI reconciles via DOM diff

Exactly how React works.

Preserving the Shiny API

You can keep:

reactive()
observe()
observeEvent()
renderPlot()
renderTable()
reactiveValues()


But their meaning changes:

Shiny	New system
Executes immediately	Registers node
Captures closures	Records expressions
Static graph	Versioned graph
Restart on change	Diff on change

Most apps would “just work”.

Where compatibility breaks (honestly)

These Shiny patterns would break or be restricted:

❌ Non-deterministic side effects
observe({
  write.csv(data(), "x.csv")
})


Hot reload requires:

Idempotence

Replayability

Side effects must be:

Explicit

Declared

Opt-in

❌ Meta-programming tricks
get(paste0("output$", id)) <- renderText(...)


Graph builder can’t reliably detect this.

❌ Direct environment mutation
counter <<- counter + 1


This destroys state tracking.

What you gain beyond hot reload

Once you make this shift, you get modern features “for free”:

✅ True hot reload

Preserve state

No browser refresh

✅ Time-travel debugging

Replay reactivity

Inspect graph versions

✅ Deterministic execution

Testable

Serializable

✅ Serverless / WASM R

Graph can run anywhere

Real-world precedents (this matters)

This is not hypothetical.

System	Did this
React	JSX → Fiber
Vue 3	Proxy-based graph
SolidJS	Signals
Observable	Reactive IR
SwiftUI	Declarative diffing

Shiny is the outlier, not the rule.

Why this hasn’t happened in R yet

Three reasons:

R lacks a strong IR culture

Backward compatibility pressure

Small ecosystem compared to JS

But technically? Entirely doable.

A realistic implementation strategy
Phase 1 — Shiny-compatible core

Reimplement reactive(), observe()

Build IR

No hot reload yet

Phase 2 — Dev-mode hot reload

File watcher

Graph diffing

State preservation

Phase 3 — UI reconciliation

Replace Shiny JS client

DOM diff instead of replace

Phase 4 — Strict mode

Enforce purity

Warn on side effects

Naming this honestly

This would not be “Shiny 2”.

It would be:

shinyx

reactR

fluxR

signalR (already taken 😄)

And it would:

Run Shiny apps

But not be Shiny

Bottom line

Yes — you can build a shiny-like system with hot reload that runs most Shiny apps unchanged.

But only if:

Shiny becomes a DSL

Reactivity becomes data

Execution becomes diffable

That’s a multi-year project — but a legitimate one.

